coredata.dc:description:
The recycling and reutilization of biomass wastes are significant for environmental protection and sustainable development. Recently, there have many studies on utilizing biomass wastes to produce carbon dots. Whereas, the spectrum shift effect that occurs in the quantitative application of carbon dots as fluorescent probes limits the accuracy of the quantitative analysis. In this work, waste tobacco leaves were used as the carbon source for synthesizing a novel carbon dots (CDs(WTL)) through a facile hydrothermal method. The CDs(WTL) possess a series of excellent properties, including good water solubility, well stability, and high fluorescence quantum yield. The fluorescent intensity of the CDs(WTL) can be quenched by tetracycline (TC) obviously, but there is a spectrum shift. In order to use the CDs(WTL) as fluorescent probes to quantify TC with higher accuracy, a quantification fluorescence model (QFM) was introduced to overcome this spectrum shift effect that often occurs. The coefficient of determination (R

      2
   ) of traditional quantification model (TQ), partial least squares (PLS), and QFM are 0.9672, 0.9834, and 0.9991, respectively; the average relative predictive error (ARPE) of TQ, PLS, and QFM are 8.8%, 4.5%, and 3.9% for the spiked water samples, and 21.9%, 22.0%, and 2.9% for spiked tablet samples, respectively. The obtained results suggest that QFM is more accurate than PLS and TQ for the TC detection. By utilizing QFM, the spike recoveries (mean ± standard deviation) in three kinds of real tablet samples produced by different manufacturers are 98.9 ± 3.6%, 102.5 ± 6.2%, and 98.5 ± 2.7%, respectively; the spike recovery in river water samples is 99.4 ± 5.0%. In addition, high performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) was used as a reference method, the F and t tests suggest that there are no significant differences on the precision and accuracy between QFM and HPLC methods.

ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
The recycling and reutilization of biomass wastes are significant for environmental protection and sustainable development. Recently, there have many studies on utilizing biomass wastes to produce carbon dots. Whereas, the spectrum shift effect that occurs in the quantitative application of carbon dots as fluorescent probes limits the accuracy of the quantitative analysis. In this work, waste tobacco leaves were used as the carbon source for synthesizing a novel carbon dots (CDs(WTL)) through a facile hydrothermal method. The CDs(WTL) possess a series of excellent properties, including good water solubility, well stability, and high fluorescence quantum yield. The fluorescent intensity of the CDs(WTL) can be quenched by tetracycline (TC) obviously, but there is a spectrum shift. In order to use the CDs(WTL) as fluorescent probes to quantify TC with higher accuracy, a quantification fluorescence model (QFM) was introduced to overcome this spectrum shift effect that often occurs. The coefficient of determination (R

                        2
                     ) of traditional quantification model (TQ), partial least squares (PLS), and QFM are 0.9672, 0.9834, and 0.9991, respectively; the average relative predictive error (ARPE) of TQ, PLS, and QFM are 8.8%, 4.5%, and 3.9% for the spiked water samples, and 21.9%, 22.0%, and 2.9% for spiked tablet samples, respectively. The obtained results suggest that QFM is more accurate than PLS and TQ for the TC detection. By utilizing QFM, the spike recoveries (mean ± standard deviation) in three kinds of real tablet samples produced by different manufacturers are 98.9 ± 3.6%, 102.5 ± 6.2%, and 98.5 ± 2.7%, respectively; the spike recovery in river water samples is 99.4 ± 5.0%. In addition, high performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) was used as a reference method, the F and t tests suggest that there are no significant differences on the precision and accuracy between QFM and HPLC methods.

ce:section.ce:para:
While for traditional univariate quantification model TQ based on the variation of signal at the maximal fluorescence emission wavelength, the coefficient of determination (R

                              2
                           ) was 0.9672 (Fig. 9c), much worse than that of QFM. Additionally, the recovery for validation set was 101.6 ± 8.6%. The prediction result for lower concentration was also incorrect, after eliminating the lowest concentration sample, the recovery turned to 102.8 ± 12.1%. Even though, the result is also worse than that obtained from QFM. The main reason for the unsatisfactory results for PLS and TQ is the red-shift of the maximal emission wavelength. The maximal fluorescence wavelength of the CDs(WTL) turned red-shift as TC concentration increased, which made the PLS and TQ fail to acquire satisfactory results for calibration set, let alone validation set, real samples, and corresponding spiked samples.

For the sake of confirming the accuracy of the results obtained from QFM based on the fluorescence quenching system of the CDs(WTL), the HPLC reference method has been carried out to detect the actual content of TC in these three kinds of tablet samples (Fig. 10
                        ). For the determination of TC in these three kinds of tables by the HPLC reference method, the coefficient of determination (R
                        2) of the calibration model is 0.9979, the spike recoveries are 100.2 ± 6.4%, 99.2 ± 10.5%, and 98.5 ± 7.4%, respectively. These results indicate that the HPLC reference method has been established properly; the predicted concentrations of TC (mean ± standard deviation) by the HPLC method are 35.71 ± 0.75, 18.75 ± 1.78, and 18.66 ± 1.78 μM, respectively.
